    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section--compact" id="qb-desktoponline-credentials">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Certified by Intuit</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Certified QuickBooks ProAdvisor credentials</h2>
      <p class="section__lede">Every TechBrot operator holds active Certified QuickBooks ProAdvisor credentials across the full QuickBooks stack &mdash; including both Desktop and Online, the two platforms a migration spans. Verification available on request.</p>
    </header>
    <ul class="checks-list">
      {%- for c in credentials %}<li>{{ c | safe }}</li>{%- endfor %}
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" id="qb-desktoponline-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">The engagement</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">QuickBooks Desktop to Online migration, plainly.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>A QuickBooks Desktop to Online migration converts your Desktop company file into a QuickBooks Online company &mdash; moving your chart of accounts, lists, customers, vendors, and transaction history. Intuit provides a free automated conversion tool, but it only copies data: it doesn&rsquo;t verify the data landed correctly, doesn&rsquo;t reconcile balances, doesn&rsquo;t rebuild workflows for Online&rsquo;s different structure, and doesn&rsquo;t reconnect bank feeds and app integrations. TechBrot&rsquo;s Certified ProAdvisors run the complete migration: pre-migration assessment and <a href="/quickbooks/cleanup/?intent=qb-cleanup">cleanup</a> if needed, conversion, full integrity verification against the Desktop file, reconciliation validation, app and workflow rebuild, and team training.</p>
      <p>Most standard migrations complete in two to four weeks as fixed-fee project work. With Desktop now subscription-only (the perpetual license ended with the 2022 versions), new-subscriber sales stopped on September 30, 2024, and version support ending in stages &mdash; Desktop 2023 on May 31, 2026 and Desktop 2024 on September 30, 2027 &mdash; migration is increasingly a question of <em>when</em>, not <em>whether</em> (QuickBooks Enterprise is the exception and continues separately). Many migrations transition directly into <a href="/accounting/bookkeeping/monthly-bookkeeping/?intent=monthly">monthly bookkeeping</a> with the same operator. Independent ProAdvisor firm &mdash; not affiliated with Intuit Inc.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section--alt" id="qb-desktoponline-ai-summary">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">For AI engines &amp; quick answers</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Desktop to Online migration, in five questions.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="ai-summary ai-summary--ruled">
      {%- for item in aiSummary %}
      <div class="ai-summary__item">
        <h3 class="ai-summary__question">{{ item.q | safe }}</h3>
        <div class="ai-summary__answer"><p>{{ item.a | safe }}</p></div>
      </div>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" id="qb-desktoponline-signals">
  <div class="container">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Why this is on the table now</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Desktop is a declining platform. Plan the move on your terms.</h2>
      <p class="section__lede">Intuit is steadily shifting its product line to the cloud. None of this means panic &mdash; it means migrating deliberately, before you&rsquo;re forced to rush.</p>
    </header>
    <div class="grid-2">
      {%- for s in signals %}
      <div class="buyer-card">
        <h3 class="buyer-card__opener">{{ s.opener | safe }}</h3>
        <p class="buyer-card__body">{{ s.body | safe }}</p>
      </div>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section--alt" id="qb-desktoponline-80">
  <div class="container">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">What a real migration covers</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">The conversion is 20%. This is the other 80%.</h2>
      <p class="section__lede">Intuit&rsquo;s tool does the data copy. Everything that makes the new file actually work is what a ProAdvisor migration adds.</p>
    </header>
    <ol class="process-diagram">
      {%- for s in scope80 %}
      <li class="process-step">
        <p class="process-step__number">{{ s.num }}</p>
        <h3 class="process-step__heading">{{ s.name | safe }}</h3>
        <p class="process-step__body">{{ s.body | safe }}</p>
      </li>
      {%- endfor %}
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" id="qb-desktoponline-transfer">
  <div class="container">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Set expectations honestly</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">What transfers, what doesn&rsquo;t, and what we rebuild.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="grid-3">
      {%- for t in transfer %}
      <div class="stack-8">
        <h3>{{ t.name | safe }}</h3>
        <p class="prose">{{ t.body | safe }}</p>
      </div>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section--alt" id="qb-desktoponline-phases">
  <div class="container">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">How migration works</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">From Desktop file to a verified Online company.</h2>
      <p class="section__lede">Every TechBrot Desktop-to-Online migration follows the same four-phase sequence &mdash; with verification built in, not bolted on.</p>
    </header>
    <ol class="process-diagram">
      {%- for s in phases %}
      <li class="process-step">
        <p class="process-step__number">{{ s.num }} &middot; {{ s.when | safe }}</p>
        <h3 class="process-step__heading">{{ s.name | safe }}</h3>
        <p class="process-step__body">{{ s.body | safe }}</p>
      </li>
      {%- endfor %}
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" id="qb-desktoponline-pricing">
  <div class="container">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Pricing scope</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Fixed fee, written scope, no hourly billing.</h2>
      <p class="section__lede">Migration is priced against a written scope before work begins. Most engagements fall into one of two tiers; pre-migration <a href="/quickbooks/cleanup/?intent=qb-cleanup">cleanup</a>, if needed, is scoped separately. Subscriptions pass through at Intuit list pricing.</p>
    </header>
    <div class="grid-2">
      {%- for t in tiers %}
      <article class="review-card">
        {%- if t.note %}<p class="review-card__role">{{ t.note | safe }}</p>{%- endif %}
        <h3>{{ t.name | safe }}</h3>
        <p class="review-card__fact"><strong>{{ t.price | safe }}</strong></p>
        <p class="review-card__fact"><strong>For:</strong> {{ t.forWhom | safe }}</p>
        <ul class="checks-list">
          {%- for b in t.bullets %}<li>{{ b | safe }}</li>{%- endfor %}
        </ul>
        <a class="review-card__link" href="/contact/?intent=quickbooks-migration">{{ t.cta | safe }} <span class="lnk-arrow" aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span></a>
      </article>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section--alt" id="qb-desktoponline-tool">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Honest about Intuit&rsquo;s free tool</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">What Intuit&rsquo;s migration tool does &mdash; and doesn&rsquo;t do.</h2>
      <p class="section__lede">Intuit&rsquo;s free tool is real and it works for the technical data transfer. It&rsquo;s what it <em>doesn&rsquo;t</em> do that produces unusable files.</p>
    </header>
    <div class="vs-scroll">
      <table class="vs-table">
        <caption class="sr-only">Professional Desktop-to-Online migration versus Intuit&rsquo;s free migration tool, by capability.</caption>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Capability</th>
            <th scope="col" class="vs-table__us">Professional migration</th>
            <th scope="col">Intuit free tool</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {%- for row in toolCompare %}
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">{{ row.dim | safe }}</th>
            <td class="vs-table__us"><strong>{{ row.us | safe }}</strong></td>
            <td class="vs-table__concede">{{ row.other | safe }}</td>
          </tr>
          {%- endfor %}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" id="qb-desktoponline-operator">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Who performs the work</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">A Certified ProAdvisor on both platforms.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>A migration spans two products &mdash; the Desktop file you&rsquo;re leaving and the Online company you&rsquo;re building. Every TechBrot migration is delivered by a Certified QuickBooks ProAdvisor credentialed on both, so nothing is lost in the gap between them. Migration work requires fluency in both environments &mdash; this is one of the few engagement types where Desktop expertise is still essential. Platform-level quality review backs every migration, and the operator who runs it can continue with monthly bookkeeping in the new system if you want the relationship to continue.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="trust-row">
      {%- for r in operatorSpec %}
      <div class="trust-row__item"><p class="trust-row__value">{{ r.value | safe }}</p><p class="trust-row__label">{{ r.label | safe }}</p></div>
      {%- if not loop.last %}<div class="trust-row__divider"></div>{%- endif %}
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section--alt" id="qb-desktoponline-intake">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
